Fluid Layouts:

	*HTML*
	<h1>
	  It is quite a three pipe problem.
	  <a href="#">Please get me a pipe.</a>
	</h1>

	*CSS*
	h1 {
  		font-size: 30px;
  		font-weight: bold;
	}

	Converting Pixels to ems:

	 html {
  		font-size: 16px;
	}

	body {
	  color: #352a25;
	  font-family: Georgia, serif;
	  font-size: 62.5%; /* 1em = 10px */
	}

	**In the above we set a font-size for the html to give the browser something to work with and then in the body we set the font-size to be a proportion of the html font size-specifically we set the font-size to be 62.5% of the original font-size of 16px. This gives us a font-size in the body of 10px.

	em: target ÷ context = result

	em example: 30px [targer font size] ÷ 10px [default browser font size] = 3em

	Fluid Layout: 

		h1 {
  			font-size: 3em; /* 30px/10px */
  			font-weight: bold;
		}

	Fluid Layout Transformation: need to convert the font-size to em
	
	h1 a {
		font-size: 14px;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		text-decoration: none;
		color: #6C564B;	
  	}

  	The value we need to set ems at is calculated thusly: target ÷ context = result
  	The value we need to set ems at is calculated thusly: target[14px] ÷ 10px [default browser font size]=1.4em 
  	1.4em is the adjusted display size.

  		h1 a {
		font-size: 1.4em; /*14px÷10px*/
		text-transform: uppercase;
		text-decoration: none;
		color: #6C564B;	
  		}

